Event.festival_dish_description: Housemade tomato rigatoni with tiger prawns in a cream, tomato and vodka sauce with sweet chilli, garlic and Hong Kong-style ‘Typhoon Shelter’ crumb
Event.wellington_story:
1154 AD was the first clear reference to pasta recorded, charting trade from the Port of Sicily. 868 years later, in our own little port on the other side of the world, we continue the journey. 

Inspired by the trading of culture, stories and produce that would've come through Wellington Harbour, 1154 Pastaria are 'trading' in flavours from the port of Hong Kong, and re-imagining one of their classics. They've paired Alla Vodka sauce with Hong Kong "Typhoon Shelter" prawns, a style of cooking well-known among sailors and typical of locals in the harbour sheltering from storms and in doing so have created the story of Wellington's Port in a bowl.

Event.one_sentence_description: Congress' takeover of 50-50 restaurant
Event.short_description: Join Chef Zach Tinsley of Congress, Melbourne as he shares his signature dishes that have forged a cult following in the culinary capital of Australia. A Wellingtonian through and through, Zach will be leaning on the region's conscientious suppliers to power the punch of his flavour forward, umami-packed menu. Across eight family-style dishes, you'll experience a pig's head sanga, deftly spiced venison pastrami atop cultured cream and silky sweet n sour leeks drowned in parsnip milk. Reuniting with his mentor of 10 years, Zach will be bringing a taste of Congress to this year's Festival.
Event.long_description:
Join Chef Zach Tinsley of Congress, Melbourne as he shares his signature dishes that have forged a cult following in the culinary capital of Australia. A Wellingtonian through and through, Zach will be leaning on the regions conscientious suppliers to power the punch of his flavor forward, umami packed sharing style menu. Across eight family style dishes you'll experience a pig's head sanga that comes with the promise of a juicy explosion, deftly spiced venison pastrami atop cultured cream and silky sweet n sour leeks drowned in parsnip milk. 

Reuniting with his mentor of 10 years, Zach will have access to 50-50 Chef Helen Turnbull's kitchen, garden and staff as he brings a serious taste of the hatted Congress to this year's Festival.

Event.title: The Sea Breeze Inn
Event.short_description:
Drawing on the classic Kiwi corner fish and chip shop and nostalgic family restaurants from our childhood, Morgan McGlone will once again help us open the festival with a bang. He'll be reinterpreting Kiwi classics with New Zealand’s freshest and most sustainable seafood.

Popping up in an old car mechanics, it will be transformed into your new favourite seafood experience, expect oysters a plenty, fish & chips, paua fritters, clams and seafood chowder. Beer-hall style seating, and beers to match by Garage Project. 

Proudly brought to you by Visa.
Event.long_description:
It's time to celebrate Aotearoa New Zealand's fresh, seasonal and sustainable kaimoana in this three-night Festival Opening Event - Welcome to The Sea Breeze Inn!

Join well-known Festival lover and chef, Morgan McGlone, who will lead a team to bring you your favourite seafood treats. With a nod to nostalgic childhood family restaurants, expect classics to be reinterpreted, including fish and chips, fritters, chowder, a raw bar and more. You'll find us popping up in an old car mechanics workshop with friends Garage Project and more. So pop 'inn' for the night. Don't miss out on getting your hands on some of Aotearoa's finest seafood for a limited time only.

Proudly brought to you by Visa.

Event.wellington_story: Astoria was formerly the Midland Hotel. Built in 1915 by architect Henry Eli White as a five-floor building in the Spanish mission-style. The hotel was demolished in 1982 and the site was developed by Wellington City Council as Midland Park. Astoria was established in 1996 and is one of the oldest surviving hospitality establishments in the city. Nato Dalla Terra means "born of the earth". This dish represents the rebirth of the iconic Wellington restaurant, Astoria, whilst paying respect to its rich history.

Event.title: Chef Successions: Black Estate at Atlas
Event.keywords: chef collab, black estate, fine dining
Event.one_sentence_description: Join us as we welcome Olly Le Maitre, Head Chef of Black Estate, into Atlas as part of our Chef Successions.
Event.short_description:
Born in the UK and raised in Wellington, Head Chef of Black Estate, Olly Le Maitre’s food education began at 15, as an apprentice at Logan Brown. After several years, he ventured to Matterhorn, then Whitebait, where Le Maitre says he “started finding my rhythm with food”. 
After working in luxury lodges in Australia and New Zealand he has settled at Black Estate winery, named Best Winery Restaurant at the 2019 Cuisine Awards, as their new Head Chef.

Event.keywords: chef collab, alta, fine dining
Event.one_sentence_description: Join us as we welcome, Georgia Van Prehn, Head Chef and Owner of Alta, into Atlas as part of our Chef Successions.
Event.short_description:
Georgia Van Prehn, Head Chef and Owner of Alta, was born in Hong Kong, raised in Singapore and spent her teenage years in New Zealand before she headed to the restaurant meccas of Melbourne and London to pursue her career as a Chef.  

After returning home to New Zealand. She worked at Scotch restaurant in Blenheim as their Head Chef and after a few short years opened her own restaurant, Alta, in Auckland. Event.title: Chef Successions: Mapu at Atlas
Event.keywords: chef collab, mapu, fine dining, Chef of the Year, Giulio Sturla
Event.one_sentence_description: Join us as we welcome Giulio Sturla, Head Chef and Owner of Mapu, into Atlas as part of our Chef Successions.
Event.short_description:
Giulio Sturla was the chef and creator of New Zealand's Restaurant of the Year 2015, Roots in Lyttelton, outside Christchurch. At Roots, Giulio focused on experimenting with local ingredients and delivering these in new and exciting dishes. Roots received many accolades, one of which, was being named the only three-hatted restaurant outside of Auckland and Giulio was named Chef of the Year in 2018. 
Fast forward to 2021 and Giulio has a new passion project, his test kitchen Mapu, and once again the locally foraged and sourced ingredients are the highlight.

Event.title: Chef Successions: Des Harris & Martin Bosley at Atlas
Event.keywords: chef collab, fine dining, Des Harris, Martin Bosley
Event.one_sentence_description: Join us as we welcome the great Chefs Des Harris & Martin Bosley into Atlas as part of our Chef Successions.
Event.short_description:
Atlas welcomes the great Chefs Des Harris and Martin Bosely. 
Originally from Wellington, Chef Des Harris spent his formative years leading the kitchen at Logan Brown Restaurant under Chef Al Brown. Since then, Harris has achieved many accolades within the industry. 
With over 30 years of experience in New Zealand’s restaurants, chef-restaurateur, columnist, and author Martin Bosley has cemented his name among the greats. Living by the philosophy that we should eat what’s in season, what’s local and what’s fresh, Martin has been bestowed with every major food award NZ has to offer.
Event.long_description:
Originally from Wellington, Des spent his formative years leading the kitchen at Logan Brown Restaurant under Chef Al Brown. 

Since then, Des has achieved many accolades within the industry including leading the Martinborough Hotel restaurant to win the best Regional Restaurant category in the Cuisine awards within his first year, being awarded Chef of the Year in 2013, leading Clooney restaurant, Auckland to a three-hat standard and opening Augustus Bistro,  which was regarded as one of the best new restaurants of its year. 

 In 2021, Des expanded his offerings to bring great food to people’s homes, aiming to create a personal experience, one which his clients can truly relax.



With over 30 years experience in New Zealand’s restaurants, chef-restaurateur, columnist, author Martin Bosley has cemented his name among the greats.

Living by the philosophy that we should eat what’s in season, what’s local and what’s fresh, Martin has been bestowed with every major food award NZ has to offer. Celebrating Wellington’s artisan and bespoke producers and embracing the epic efforts of winemakers, farmers and fishermen, Martin helps keep the multicultural, diverse cuisine of New Zealand alive.

 Though he no longer owns a restaurant, Martin owns a seafood supply company and is usually busy with catering work for weddings and other events around Aotearoa New Zealand.

$185 Meal Only
$290 Meal & Wine Match
Event.event_title: Chef Successions: Des Harris & Martin Bosley at Atlas

Event.title: A Slice of the Outback with Mark Olive
Event.kid_friendly: Yes but they must be accompanied by an adult
Event.one_sentence_description: Experience a slice of the outback with Indigenous Australian cuisine served by charismatic chef and Bundjalung man, Mark Olive, hosted at the Australian High Commissioner’s residence.
Event.short_description: Experience bush tucker brought to you by Australia’s renowned Indigenous chef Mark Olive. A fine-dining experience with a twist, we’re serving a slice of the outback in Wellington. Enjoy and learn about the cuisine of Australia’s First Nations, traditional Indigenous Australian ingredients flavoured with Mark’s own native herbs. Paired with Australia’s finest wines, Mark’s charisma, and the ambience of the Australian High Commissioner’s residence, it’s a dining experience you don't want to miss. Diners will receive a copy of Mark Olive’s recipe book The Outback Café to take home.
Event.long_description:
Experience bush tucker like you haven’t before. Renowned Indigenous Australian chef Mark Olive brings a four-course meal from the First Nations of Australia to Pōneke Wellington. A Bundjalung man, and specialist in contemporary outback flavours, Mark’s family hails from the Northern Rivers region of New South Wales. 

Hosted at the Australian High Commissioner’s residence, the dining experience will feature traditional ingredients including wallaby, kangaroo, crocodile and barramundi, the fresh exciting taste of lemon myrtle, wattle seed, pepper berry, and Mark’s very own native Australian herbs. Finished with a twist on the much-contested pavlova loved on both sides of the ditch. Served alongside the bush tucker are Australia’s finest wines. 

Hear the traditional knowledge of First Nations cuisine, learn and experience bush tucker served, piping hot like the red earth itself. Diners are encouraged to bring the unique indigenous flavours they experience at this event to their own kitchens, receiving a copy of Mark Olive’s recipe book The Outback Café to take home.
Event.event_title: A Slice of the Outback with Mark Olive

Event.title: Around the World
Event.keywords: gluten free, vegan, vegetarian, travel, bambuchisan, around the world, global culture
Event.one_sentence_description: It's travelling tastebud time, we're off around the world!
Event.short_description: Oh the places you'll taste, as you circumnavigate the gastronomic globe on this tasty adventure. Dine on dishes from all over the world from countries past and present staff have connections with. The first half of the festival seeing you travel around the southern hemisphere and then fly north for the second half and dine on the best of the northern hemisphere. Grab your passport, and get a stamp for each country. Complete your around the world gastronomic tour and claim your prize.
Event.long_description:
Oh the places you'll taste, as you circumnavigate the gastronimc globe on this tasty adventure. Dine on dishes from all over the world from countries past and present staff have connections with. Starting in the Southern Hemisphere for the first two weeks, with dishes inspired by the cuisines of Aotearoa, Australia, Fiji, Indonesia, and South Africa. The second half of the festival will see you travelling North with dishes inspired by Canada, Mexico, Japan, France, and the Czech Republic. You'll go adventuring with the beverages too, with inventive takes on classic cocktails from all over the globe. Grab your passport, and get a stamp for each country. Complete your around the world gastromnic tour and you can claim your prize. 

First two weeks - Southern Hemisphere: 

New Zealand 
Lamb rump (smoked and sous vide), confit fennel, mint paste, kawakawa jus 
Paua/shellfish fritters

Australia 
GF damper with rosemary and house made cultured butter
Chicken parmigiana

South Africa 
Bobotie, simmered minced meat with curry powder and spices and baked in a egg and milk mixture 
Boerewors, traditional south african sausage served with chakalaka (vegetable relish)

Fiji
Kokada, Fresh fish sourced from Moana, cured in coconut cream, lime and chilli 
Taro curry, rich and spicy vegetarian taro curry

Indonesia
Nasi goreng, classic fried noodles with chicken, pork or a vegetarian option topped with a fried quail egg spring onion chutney and sweet soy sauce.
Satay skewer, cooked over hot charcoal and finished with a fermented sambal and peanut sauce 

Second two weeks - Northern Hemisphere:

Canada
Maple bacon poutine, fries with gravy and maple bacon pieces and cheese curds from Kingsmeade and sriracha ketchup 
Salmon pate

Japan
Okonomiyaki, a savoury salted cabbage pancake with house cured crispy pork belly
Unagi, grilled eel 

France 
Bourguignon
French onion soup 

Poland
Bigos, Meat stew with sauerkraut and fresh cabbage 
Wild mushrooms, sauteed, roasted, poached. Different mushroom textures and cooking techniques 

Mexico 
Fish tostada, mango salsa, coriander, lime
Esquites

Event.festival_dish_description: Pumpkin and dairy-free Bongusto mascarpone ravioli, with caramelised pumpkin, housegrown sage and garlic vegan butter sauce, toasted pumpkin seeds, dehydrated pumpkin skin, foraged nasturtium, and dairy-free parmesan Pandoro pangrattato
Event.wellington_story:
Wellington's hospitality scene is making great strides to reduce food waste and Beach Babylon supports these endeavours. This dish is inspired by Wellington City Council's Te Atakura - First to Zero campaign, working towards zero net carbon emissions by 2050. 

Designed with low carbon emissions and low food waste principles in mind, and utilising local produce, all parts of Wellington-grown pumpkin are used, from the seeds to flesh and skin. For every Festival Dish sold,$1 will be donated to offset emissions through Te Rahi O Tane -Trees That Count; planting native trees to help the future generations.

Event.keywords:
Zero Waste
Sustainability 
Kaibosh
Donation
Groups
Four course menu
Wine matched
Beer matches
Event.one_sentence_description: Beach Babylon and Kaibosh invite you to a three course and Matahiwi wine and ParrotDog beer matched zero waste dining experience.
Event.short_description: A zero-waste feast that’s created using 100% rescued food from Wellington artisan and producers. Beach Babylon, in collaboration with Kaibosh, invite you to a three-course, Matahiwi wine and ParrotDog beer matched dining experience inspired by the roots to shoots food movement and championing the ten most wasted food items in New Zealand. You’ll learn about the big issue of food waste and how you can minimise it from a Kaibosh expert and enjoy some great food and drink along the way. Part of the proceeds will be donated to Kaibosh Food Rescue.
Event.long_description:
Did you know that food waste going to landfill is a significant contributor to New Zealand's carbon emissions?

Beach Babylon, in collaboration with Kaibosh, invite you to a three-course zero waste dining experience. You'll feast on a menu created from 100% rescued food from great Wellington producers and suppliers such as Capital Produce, Pandoro, Zany Zeus, Carello Gelato, Bongusto and Island Bay Butchery, to name a few.  The menu champions the ten most wasted food items in New Zealand, inspired by the roots to shoot and nose to tail food movements the menu will be matched with low pour, clean skin and labelled damaged beverages from Matahiwi Estate and Parrotdog. You’ll learn about the big issue of food waste and how you can minimise it from a Kaibosh expert, and enjoy some great food and drink along the way. Ten percent of ticket proceeds will be donated to Kaibosh Food Rescue.
Event.event_title: Less Than Zero: A Zero Waste Dining Experience

Inspired by the ultimate state of flux, climate change, the pop-up menu focuses on local, sustainable, low-waste, roots to shoots, low carbon dishes, with live folk and protest music performances by local musicians Thursday to Sunday nights. Babylon will be dressed the part to evoke watershed moments from the past that opened our eyes to important environmental and social issues.
Event.long_description: A celebration of folk and protest music, local food, drink and moments from history that opened our eyes to important environmental and social issues. Inspired by the ultimate state of flux, climate change; their special menu focuses on low-waste, roots to shoots, low carbon food and drink, made from local and sustainably sourced ingredients.  Enjoy all this with live folk and protest music performances by local musicians Thursday to Sunday nights.  Babylon will be dressed the part to evoke imagery from watershed moments such as: Woodstock 1969, Earth Day 1970, the founding of Greenpeace 1971 and the Nambassa Festivals of 1976-1981.  Peace out!

Event.title: Across the Ages
Event.keywords: degustation
Event.one_sentence_description: The new and old come together across a seven-course degustation.
Event.short_description: Two worlds collide. The new and old come together across a seven-course degustation. Experience innovative dishes by Head Chef, Warren Maddox, across an evening that celebrates a fusion of the ages. Explore both traditional and contemporary cooking techniques, prepared side by side. Warren will lead you on a culinary journey and share his tips and tricks for the methods that he is most passionate about. Tickets include canapés, a degustation, welcome beverage and return transport to Boomrock’s incredible venue, perched along the cliff face and overlooking the Tasman Sea.
Event.long_description:
Two worlds collide. The new and old come together across a seven-course degustation. Experience innovative dishes by head chef, Warren Maddox, across an evening that celebrates a fusion of the ages.  

Explore both traditional and contemporary cooking techniques, prepared side by side. Warren will lead you on a culinary journey and share his tips and tricks for the methods that he is most passionate about.  

In keeping with the flow of time, Warren’s culinary journey matches that of cuisine itself. He began with classical training and has incorporated modern discipline over time. The seven dishes will celebrate this journey using our local flora and fauna. 

This sophisticated showcase, coupled with the unrivalled location and warm hospitality of Boomrock, will create an evening to remember. 

Tickets include a welcome beverage on arrival, canapés, degustation dinner and return transport to Boomrock’s incredible venue, perched along the cliff face and overlooking the Tasman Sea. Guests will also be given a recipe book to take home.

*Please be advised that dietaries for this event have been updated since the programme guide was printed.

Event.wellington_story: Wellington’s Botanic Gardens is located at a site of importance for generations. When Europeans arrived, there were already well established Pā’s at Pipitea and Kumutoto. The people of Te Ātiawa from Pipitea Pā used the Botanic Gardens for ngākinga (food cultivation), collecting native plants and birds. Burger Liquor has sought their inspiration from this space, in particular the rose and herb gardens, and the popular duck pond.

Many of these visitors choose to stay on in Wellington, working in hospo and travelling the country. This dish is an ode to those hospo workers who’ve had to put travel plans on hold and stay grounded in Wellington while Covid has been afoot.

Event.one_sentence_description: ITALO-ARGENTINIAN CUSINE AT CICIO CACIO
Event.short_description: Cicio Cacio will be transforming their kitchen into an authentic 'Bodegon' an Argentine-type tavern, the everyday place where writers, artists and creatives would meet in the streets of Buenos Aires. Celebrating the cooking of the Italian migrants in Argentina, there will be a feast of fresh pasta, grilled meats, schnitzels, and many more dishes that Italian grandmas brought from the old continent to the new world. Be transported to the 1900s through glasses of Malbec, handmade comfort food and the occasional tango dancer. Immerse yourself and find yourself in the streets of Buenos Aires.
Event.long_description: Cicio Cacio will be transforming their kitchen into an authentic 'Bodegon' an Argentian-type tavern, the everyday place where writers, artists and creatives would meet in the streets of Buenos Aires. Celebrating the cooking of the Italian migrants in Argentina, there will be a feast of fresh pasta, grilled meats, schnitzels, and many more dishes that Italian grandmas brought from the old continent to the new world. Be transported to the 1900s through glasses of Malbec, handmade comfort food and the occasional tango dancer. Immerse yourself and find yourself in the vibrant streets of Buenos Aires.

Event.wellington_story: For much of the 1800s and early 1900s, Wellington and the Wairarapa were a duck hunter's paradise. Duck was considered an important source of food and feathers within the Māori community and was mainly hunted using dogs and canoes. Influenced by British settlers, indigenous communities began hunting with guns, leading to larger-scale farming where meat was more easily accessible. Coene's Bar & Eatery Festival Dish this year has been developed to capture a hearty duck hunters plate

Event.one_sentence_description: Get your mates together for a night, touring Wellington's waterfront.
Event.short_description:
Get outdoors and enjoy a trip around the waterfront with stops to warm your body with winter versions of traditionally tropical cocktails. Think Coffee Supreme espresso martini, coconut and Fix & Fogg piña colada. Each cocktail will be matched with a snack to fuel your walk around the water. The crawl can be completed in one day or purchase a 'Festival Passport' and enjoy it over several days. Each venue stop includes a cocktail, beer or wine with a matching bite.

Upgrade to our 'Group Croc Bike Package', cruising in style as you make your way around six fantastic Wellington venues.
Event.long_description:
Get outdoors and enjoy a trip around the waterfront with intermittent stops to warm your body and your fingers with winter versions of traditionally tropical cocktails. Think Coffee Supreme espresso martini, coconut and Fix & Fogg piña colada. Each cocktail will be matched up with a little snack to fuel your walk around the water. The crawl can be completed in one day or purchase a 'Festival Passport' and enjoy it over several days. Each venue stop includes a cocktail, beer or wine with a matching bite.

Upgrade to our 'Group Croc Bike Package', cruising in style as you make your way around six fantastic Wellington venues.

Event.festival_dish_description: Wellington Chocolate Factory chocolate, Awatoru Wild Foods and Brooklyn Creamery goat's milk
Event.wellington_story: With Wellington being the capital, the political landscape has a huge impact on the city - you never quite know what's coming next, what effect local politics have, and does that promise made really mean what you think it does? How much honey is actually in the beehive, or is it all just hot air? Daisy's Festival Dish isn't what it seems, spinning what you think you know things taste like and turning it into something completely different. This dish is part of a three-course dessert menu that navigates local politics, PR spin and what's going on in the Beehive. Because when it comes to political promises, it's always a bit of a lolly scramble.

Event.long_description:
With their nose to the grindstone, the team at Daisy’s have really put their hearts into it and present to you the Offal Club. This is no tripe, it will be a multi-course delight, offering a banquet of offal delights featuring ingredients that are often misunderstood, all served Viking dining-hall style. 

It may seem a bit tongue ‘n’ cheek to be running this given their sister restaurant, Hillside is meatless, but the team at Daisy’s see it as the same philosophy - celebrating ingredients that are often forgotten.

Event.wellington_story: Lambton Quay was initially known as Beach St, and Wellington’s original foreshore until the 1855 Wairarapa earthquake lifted the land along the northwestern side of the harbour. The street was renamed Lambton Quay after John Lambton, the first Earl of Durham and the first chairman of directors of the New Zealand Company. Dillinger's Festival Dish represents the shoreline of 1840.

Event.keywords:
Indian
Street
Cocktails
Party
Festival
Dancing / Entertainment
Event.one_sentence_description: A little present from India... a night filled with Indian culture, food and art.
Event.short_description: A little present from India as we transform for a night filled with street food, cocktails and live Bollywood dancers. Enjoy live cooking stations, henna and games as dishes circulate throughout the evening. Expect to enjoy chat, kebabs, Indian sliders and Indo-Chinese from Mumbai alongside authentic South Indian curries and sweets. Featuring three talented chefs from Dillingers, head chef Prathamesh P Nair from Mumbai, chef Bibin Das from Kerala and chef Brigitta Josopandojo from Indonesia. The evening will take your taste buds on a journey to remember.
Event.long_description:
A little present from India as we transform for a night filled with street food, cocktails and live Bollywood dancers. Enjoy live cooking stations, henna and games as dishes circulate throughout the evening. Enjoy chat, kebabs, Indian sliders and Indo-Chinese all from Mumbai alongside authentic South Indian curries and sweets.

Featuring three talented chefs from Dillingers, head chef Prathamesh P Nair from Mumbai, Bibin Das from Kerala and Brigitta Josopandojo from Indonesia.

Prathamesh's culinary journey began in the kitchen with his mum in the culinary melting pot of Mumbai. His formal French cuisine training helps chef Prat give every dish a modern touch while still keeping it authentic to his roots.

Chef Bibin's background in ecology and biodiversity couldn't win over his love for food. Growing up in his father's restaurant, taught Bibin everything he knows about Indian food. Kerala is known as the land of spices and that's exactly what you will explore throughout Bibin's dishes.

Chef Brigitta hails from Indonesia where the influence of Indian food is everywhere. Brigitta studied at Le Cordon Bleu honing her culinary skills and now brings this blend of training and heritage to her cooking.

Event.wellington_story: Dragonfly owners, Brent Wong and Tania Siladi, were inspired by their father’s Chinese restaurant, The Jasmin, for this year’s Festival Dish. Lemon chicken was the most popular order at their father’s restaurant and Brent and Tania have fond memories of going there every day after school and feasting on this delicious dish. For their version of lemon chicken, Dragonfly is giving it a modern Japanese twist with bite-sized karaage style chicken and yuzu in the sauce. The Jasmin Licensed Chinese Restaurant was and still is, located on the mezzanine floor of the James Cook Arcade on Lambton Quay. The current owner was a former employee of their father’s, who worked his way up from kitchen hand and eventually purchased the business when their father retired.

Event.kid_friendly: Yes but they must be accompanied by an adult
Event.one_sentence_description: Field & Green continue their journey around the world celebrating the diaspora of Jewish cuisine, this year in India, for centuries home to Jewish people.
Event.short_description: Field & Green continue their journey around the world celebrating the diaspora of Jewish cuisine, this year in India, for centuries home to Jewish people. Divided into three distinct groups based on location and origin, the menu will showcase dishes from; the Cochin Jews on the Malabar Coast in Kerala, known as ‘the land of spices’; the Bene Israel community on the West Coast and their aromatic dishes; and the Baghdadi Jews from the Middle East, having settled in West Bengal, their cooking is a hybrid adding Indian spices to middle eastern dishes.
Event.long_description:
Continuing their journey around the world celebrating the diaspora of Jewish cuisine, this year head chef Laura Greenfield is off India, home to Jewish people for centuries. Divided into three distinct groups based on location and origin myths, all have adapted their original cuisines to local ingredients and influences whilst upholding kosher laws.

The Cochin Jews arrived on the Malabar Coast, Kerala, in around 50 CE and are seen as one of the ten lost tribes of Israel. Reflecting ‘the land of spices’ and its rich trading heritage, their cuisine is a meeting of cultures dominated by spices.

The Bene Israel community settled on the West Coast of India, near Mumbai, around the 2nd century and lived as oil pressers and farmers. Characterised by the cooking of the local Maharashtra people their dishes are spicy and aromatic, making use of abundant fish, with ample chilli and turmeric.

More recently, around 250 years ago, the Baghdadi Jews came from the Middle East settling in West Bengal near Kolkata. Baghdadi cooking is a hybrid, adding Indian spices to Iraqi and Syrian dishes of potatoes, raisins and tamarind.

The menu will showcase a collection of Indian Jewish dishes from each of these communities. Come and experience this delicious confluence of cuisine.

Event.short_description: Often the best course is the last course, but in this case, all courses are desserts! Over four-courses, diners will be taken through a multi-sensory experience that explores four key 'inception of place moments', inspired by the sea, land, space and beyond. Throughout history, brave souls have stepped forth into uncharted territories overcoming insurmountable odds to find out what lies in the great beyond. Over time, these once foreign lands began their transformative journey into what we now consider 'places'. This event invites guests to explore concepts of place, incrementally shifting the lens from familiarity to the great unknown.
Event.long_description:
Often the best course is the last course, but in this case, all courses are desserts! Over four-courses, diners will be taken through a multi-sensory experience that explores four key 'inception of place moments', inspired by the sea, land, space and beyond. Over time, these once foreign lands began their transformative journey into what we now consider 'places'. Event.wellington_story: Foxglove Bar & Kitchen’s Wellington story reflects the venue’s rich history. Wolf at Foxglove is the newest addition to the story of the grand old Greta Point Tavern. The building was one of the original and last remaining steamship wharf buildings converted into a tavern at Greta Point in the late 19th century. Destined for demolition, a plan was hatched to save it by cutting into 12 parts and relocating it by boat to its current site on the Wellington waterfront. Requiring a massive labour force, they relied on the goodwill of the people of Wellington, support from the industry, friends and a whole lot of Wellington ingenuity. To acknowledge that forward-thinking, invention, collaboration and spirit, Foxglove joined up with their friends at Southward Distilling to create our own little bit of history and bottle their first batch of whiskey. This whiskey plays a part in the aging process of Foxglove’s signature beef dish for this year.

Event.wellington_story: La Gallina Zoppa Zoppa is an old Napolitano Italian nursery rhyme that many Italian immigrants to Island Bay used to sing to their grandchildren. The Fratelli brothers used to hear it all the time growing up in Wellington, and this chicken cacciatore dish is a classic recipe from Naples and a staple for many Kiwi Italians, as chicken was the most common meat they could find in New Zealand. These simple recipes shaped the love of food for the brothers at Fratelli and inspired their Festival Dish.

Event.keywords: Colab, Vegetarian, Vegan, Forest, Graze, Degustation, Heaps of food, Heapsofood, Love food
Event.one_sentence_description: labita Florence from forest in Auckland will be joining forces with the graze team to create a nostalgic 5 course feast using everything from the root to the petal.
Event.short_description: How we eat and what we eat is changing. Join Graze Wine Bar and Plabita Florence of award-winning Forest in Auckland for a nostalgic vegetarian feast that reflects these important changes and champions the slow food movement: low waste, using wild and local ingredients, and sustainability. Using new and unusual ingredients is an important part of moving forward in the New Zealand food story. Chef Gordy and Chef Florence take that produce and present it in a nostalgic beverage-matched five-course menu, from root to petal.

Event.keywords:
LOT EIGHT
DRY RIVER WINES
HILLSIDE
CELEBRATION
21
25

Event.one_sentence_description: LOT EIGHT Dry River Wines Hillside Kitchen Celebration Milestones Birthday Vegetarian
Event.short_description: Colin and Nalini Baruch embarked on a journey 25 years ago setting up an olive grove with the sole purpose of one day tasting a New Zealand extra virgin olive oil. They were confident Martinborough could produce the same quality olive oils as its wines. Five years later they were proved right and Lot Eight was born. This year marks their 21st birthday and it's party time! Dry River Wines and Hillside Kitchen join Nalini and Colin to celebrate with a five-course beverage-matched celebratory dinner to salute this region's culinary and horticultural relationship, and Lot Eight's journey and milestones.
Event.long_description: Brought together over their shared love of food and wine, Colin and Nalini Baruch embarked on an exciting journey 25 years ago setting up an olive grove in Martinborough with the sole purpose of one day tasting a New Zealand extra virgin olive oil. They were confident the perfect climate and alluvial plains of Martinborough could produce the same quality olive oils as its wines. Five years later they were proved right and Lot Eight was born. This year marks their 21st birthday and it's party time! Dry River Wines and Hillside Kitchen join Nalini and Colin to celebrate with a five-course beverage-matched celebratory dinner to salute this region's long standing culinary and horticultural relationship, and Lot Eight's own journey and milestones.

Event.title: A Cinderella Celebration
Event.keywords:
Ballet 
Cinderella
Ball
Event.one_sentence_description: Shed your winter cares and celebrate the good times with a sparkling, joyful evening of fun, friendship and fabulous fairy-tale food.
Event.short_description: Polish your tiara and put on your glad rags! Join the Royal New Zealand Ballet Foundation and the Royal New Zealand Ballet for a ball of an evening with a decadent three-course meal at its heart. Delve into the RNZB’s upcoming ballet of Cinderella while enjoying Executive chef Jiwon Do's fairy tale on a plate. Start the evening with bubbles on arrival, enjoy salmon two ways, ViaVio stracciatella, coastal lamb, chocolate and more. Drinks available for purchase on the night and donations from ticket sales make ballet dreams come true.Take your seat at Hippopotamus for your Happy Ever After.
Event.long_description:
Polish your tiara and put on your glad rags!

Join the Royal New Zealand Ballet Foundation and the Royal New Zealand Ballet, in partnership with Hippopotamus, for a ball of an evening. Bring your Prince Charming or your wicked stepsisters, dress to impress, and settle in for a glittering rainbow of delight, with a decadent three-course meal at its heart.

Delve into the world of the RNZB’s upcoming production of Cinderella, a classic tale with a stylish twist. Come behind the scenes, meet the stars of the show and see what it takes to create a modern classic by Kiwi ‘dream team’: Loughlan Prior’s fabulous choreography, Emma Kingsbury’s fashion-forward designs and a musical score to make your heart skip a beat and your toes start to tap, by Claire Cowan. 

Hippopotamus’ Executive chef Jiwon Do has created a fairy tale on a plate. Firstly, enjoy a glass of bubbles on arrival and be welcomed by the stepsisters with salmon two ways. Once devoured, the magic begins with Cinderella’s ViaVio Stracciatella served with Lot Eight Curry Oil and a delicate pea tart. 

Continue the celebration with coastal lamb served with the ‘fab five’ compound butter and accompaniments. Finish the night in a magical Cinderella style, with an Ōtaki Honey and Pamu Deer Milk delight, served with Kabocha and Lucid Chocolatier. 

Before the clock strikes midnight, the Royal New Zealand Ballet Foundation will share how your support (a donation in the ticket price) helps make ballet dreams come true in Aotearoa. Drinks match available to purchase at the event. 

Take your seat at Hippopotamus for your Happy Ever After.

Event.wellington_story:
Huxley's is located in the Bowen Building opposite Parliament. George Ferguson Bowen, Bowen street’s namesake, was born in Donegal, Ireland and was the fifth Governor of New Zealand. Chef Adam shares the same Irish heritage and was inspired by Bowen's history. Bowen was sympathetic to Māori issues with the crown, and clearly able to see the links between the occupation of his birth land and the colonisation of Māori land. Many early Irish settlers disputed being described as Pākehā and much preferred to be known as Aohiri, or Irish.

So to celebrate the life of George Fergusson Bowen, and all the Aorihi that followed in his footsteps, Huxleys presents a Festival Dish foraged in his honour.

Event.title: Bee Happy
Event.one_sentence_description: Come celebrate the humble Honey Bee and all that it provides for us.
Event.short_description: Bee-ing home to the famous Beehive, what could be better than raising awareness of the local honey bee population. Enjoy a drink on arrival and a set-menu brunch created by chef Adam Brack-Sinnott celebrating local honey and its by-products, including pollen, honeycomb and other ingredients that are just the bee's knees. Bespoke beverages made with local honey will be available to purchase. Members of Wellington's Beekeepers Association will share their knowledge on caring for the bees and how to be a part of their ongoing conservation. Finish with a walk to the Botanic Gardens to visit thriving local bee colonies.
Event.long_description:
Bee-ing that Wellington is home to the famous Beehive, what could be better than raising awareness of the local honey bee population. Enjoy a complimentary drink on arrival, and a set menu brunch created by Chef Adam Brack-Sinnott to celebrate wonderful local honey and its bi-products, including pollen, honeycomb and other ingredients that are the bee's knees. Bespoke beverages made with local honey that may pack a sting and featuring Coffee Supreme will be available to purchase. 

Members of Wellington's Beekeepers Association will share their knowledge on caring for the bees and how to be a part of their ongoing conservation. Finish with a walk to the Botanic Gardens to visit the local bee colonies, thriving right in the heart of Wellington.

Event.short_description: During this waste-free cooking class, you’ll learn how to create delicious one-pot meals that are good for you and the planet. Former chef and now an agent with NZ Sotheby’s International, Suzette was born in the Philippines. She has seen first-hand the impacts of hunger and poverty, so food waste is something truly close to her heart.
Event.long_description:
Support Kaibosh Food Rescue in their battle against food poverty and food waste. Join innovative
Wellington and Kāpiti chefs for a series of hands-on workshops to create taste out of food that you
may previously have viewed as unwanted or waste, turning it into a delicious and sensory
experience. Dine together afterwards to share the kai and ponder how we can continue on our food-
waste revolution. Challenge your ideas around food waste and learn from those that are helping
lead the charge to a more sustainable food system.

Event.title: Mise En Place: Everything in Place by Billie Culy
Event.short_description:
Mise En Place is a series of new photographic works by Billie Culy. Inspired by place and nature, Mise En Place explores elements of domestic environments removed from their intended spaces as they respond to their natural surroundings. 

Napier-based Culy is a multi-disciplinary artist, working primarily in photography, painting and sculptural work. Attempting to reconfigure the treatment of these mediums, Culy creates imagined worlds, a sense of escapism, exploring notions of memory, nostalgia and the importance we place on our surroundings. Her works are both records of places and objects, as well as carefully composed explorations of pigment, light and texture.
Event.long_description:
Mise En Place is a series of new photographic works by Billie Culy. Inspired by place and nature, Mise En Place explores elements of domestic environments removed from their intended spaces as they respond to their natural surroundings.

Event.wellington_story: In the 1970s Ruth Pretty saw a charming old building in Kelburn and created one of Wellington's first fine dining restaurants, Marbles. In 2010 the Kelburn Village Pub was founded in its stead. While the Kelburn Village Pub is not a fine dining establishment, the winds of change always leave an imprint on tradition and the team upholds some of the traditions instilled here in the 1970s. This festival offering combines long-cherished dishes from different parts of the world adding a hint of something new and unexpected. Arthur Wellesley, the first Duke of Wellington, earned the nickname the 'Iron Duke' for his traditional political fortitude, however, there is evidence that suggests he was more open-minded than his nickname suggests. This Festival Dish celebrates the more tender, worldly side of the Duke.

Event.one_sentence_description: Egg poaching competition
Event.short_description: Caffe L'affare know a thing or two about eggs. After all, they've been poaching them for more than 30 years. The team will be honouring their one billionth poached egg by hosting an egg poaching competition at their purpose-built studio at their College St café. Dare if you will to brave the challenge and go head to head with some of College Street's best poachers. Come along for drinks, canapés and high stakes ovicular competition, and learn the best tips and tricks with an informative egg poaching lesson. Will you crack under the pressure?

Event.one_sentence_description: Experience the state of flux from our chefs being challenged to change their thinking to planet based cuisine!
Event.short_description: Traditional French cuisine is heavy on the meat and light on the plants. Le Cordon Bleu have challenged their chefs to change their thinking and apply traditional French techniques to the beautiful plant-based ingredients available here in Aotearoa, New Zealand. Event.keywords: cheese, cheeses, french cheeses, tasting, Le Marche Francais, workshop, 5 senses, European cheeses, France, NZ cheeses
Event.kid_friendly: Yes but they must be accompanied by an adult
Event.one_sentence_description: Exploring cheese with the 5 senses through different workshops
Event.short_description: Cheese isn't just a story of taste but involves all the senses. We look, eat, smell, touch, and even more surprisingly, listen to it. How can we awaken all our senses to truly appreciate the subtleties of a cheese? Le Marche Francais will help you discover the influence of all the senses on how you understand and taste cheese. Be guided and use each of the senses to taste ten cheeses from Europe and New Zealand in this friendly, interactive, fun, and playful workshop. Each guest will take home a cheese platter to enjoy with their loved ones.
Event.long_description: Cheese isn't just a story of taste but involves all the senses. We look, eat, smell, touch, and even more surprisingly, listen to it. Be guided and use each of the senses to taste ten cheeses from Europe and New Zealand in this friendly, interactive, fun, and playful workshop. Each guest will take home a cheese platter to enjoy with their loved ones.

The scrumptious men includes:
Dunkers - harder cookies that can take a dipping

Filled - cookies with a gooey filling

Event.wellington_story: Little Beer Quarter’s Festival Dish is inspired by the history of 6 Edward Street, a site that has had a presence in Wellington’s nightlife since the 1970s. Ma Maison, Champerelle, La Spagnetta, Tupulo… 6 Edward Street has an illustrious past, and this dish revisits and reworks quintessential flavours from these histories. LBQ's re-interpretation goes beyond the white button mushroom and reduced cream to celebrate the diversity and quality of produce now readily available in Te Whanganui-a-Tara.

Event.one_sentence_description: We're heading back to the 70's at Little Beer Quarter this August.
Event.short_description: Join the Beer Quarter and head back to the 70s, but don’t worry there will be more than three different coloured beers on tap. They’ll be dropping things in aspic, dusting off the Jell-o moulds and shaking up some classic cocktails. Their all-day menu is turning back the clock with new takes on asparagus rolls, deviled eggs, crumbed camembert and everyone’s favourite guilty pleasure, pineapple on pizza. No dodgy light entertainment and dad jokes here, just good wholesome food and drink with the friendly folks of 6 Edward St.
Event.long_description: Join the LBQ and head back to the 70s, but don't worry there will be more than three different coloured beers on tap. Event.one_sentence_description: Funk music and fondue, a 1970s marriage in heaven.  Grab your keys and join the dinner party with three funkiclious fondue courses matched with fine craft beer and cocktails.
Event.short_description: Funk music and fondue, a 1970s marriage in heaven. Grab your keys and join the dinner party with three funkalicious fondue courses matched with craft beer and cocktails. Think ferments, sours, Bretts and everything funky. Stinky cheese fondue and crudites to start, followed by Japanese curry fondue with chicken and eggplant katsu, finishing with Fix & Fogg Peanut butter/Wellington Chocolate Factory chocolate fondue served with pretzels and tidbits. All this with a funk music DJ spinning some classics. Recommended for groups of four or more, share an authentic '70s fondue pot with your crew.
Event.long_description: Funk music and fondue, a 1970s' marriage in heaven!  Grab your keys and join the dinner party with three funkiclious fondue courses matched with craft beer and cocktails. Think ferments, sours, bretts and everything funky. Get down with stinky cheese fondue with bitter greens and crudités, Japanese curry fondue with chicken and eggplant katsu, and Fix & Fogg's peanut butter and Wellington Chocolate Factory chocolate fondue served with salted pretzels. All of this with a live funk music performance from one of Wellington's best funk 'n' soul disc jockeys. Recommended for groups of four or more, share an authentic '70s fondue pot with your crew.

Event.one_sentence_description: Cocktails for everyone: one beery cocktail at a time. Experience a classic cocktail like a Lion Red Negroni, Steinlager-ita, Monteiths Radler Collins with a Tui Foam or a Speights Old Fashioned. Or maybe something a little more contemporary.
Event.short_description:
Adding a hint of malts and hops to some seriously good cocktails in this full-blown beer cocktail takeover.
Experience a classic cocktail like a Lion Red Negroni, Steinlager-ita, Monteiths Radler Collins with a Tui Foam or a Speights Old Fashioned. Or maybe you are a fan of more contemporary offerings, in association with Parrotdog, try a Fernet and Birdseye slushy, a blueberry sour “sour” or a barley wine cosmopolitan.
Destroying beer boredom (and feeling bloated) one cocktail at a time.
Event.long_description:
Adding a hint of malts and hops to some cerealously good cocktails in this full blown beer cocktail takeover. 
Experience a classic cocktail like a Lion Red Negroni, Steinlager-ita, Monteiths Radler Collins with a Tui Foam or a Speights Old Fashioned. Or maybe you are a fan of more contemporary offerings, in association with Parrotdog, try a Fernet and Birdseye slushy, a blueberry sour “sour” or a barley wine cosmopolitan.
Destroying beer boredom, gender based drink narratives (and feeling bloated) one cocktail at a time.
Event.event_title: LOVEBeer: Yet Another Wellington Beer Bar

Event.one_sentence_description: A unique evening exploring Native Canadian cuisine.
Event.short_description: In lockdown 2020, resident chef Jonny Taggart decided to explore his ancestral history. Adopted at birth, Jonny's search uncovered he is 1/4 Native Canadian (Inuit). Jonny's interest led him to naturally interact with his culture through food. Join Jonny as he tells his story, exploring his newly found ancestry via an eight-course menu featuring wild meats, fry bread, oysters, stew and beans. A unique evening of First Nations cuisine.

Event.wellington_story: Celebrating the first Chinese Restaurant in Wellington, Master Kong is taking you back to 1948 when The Shanghai Restaurant opened its doors on Courtenay Place. It was famous for its Ching dynasty decor and extensive menu, which included well-tried Chinese dishes, and its legendary sweet and sour pork. Opened by Ng Soon Wah and his son Thomas Carr Yam Ng along with Joe Lai Choy, it was popular with local Chinese as a meeting place and a venue for mahjong. To celebrate this first of its kind, Master Kong is recreating a dish of sweet and sour pork, but it's not like any other sweet and sour you've ever seen or tasted.

Event.keywords: sauerkraut workshop fermentation Esther's class learn pickles
Event.kid_friendly: Yes but they must be accompanied by an adult
Event.one_sentence_description: Join Esther for a fun and engaging class to learn her top tips and tricks for great tasting sauerkraut
Event.short_description: Esther has perfected the art of fermentation, supplying many of Wellington's best cafes and restaurants with top quality sauerkraut and fermented condiments. In this fun, engaging and hands-on class, learn how to flavour and enhance sauerkraut recipes for a winning batch every time, troubleshoot common mistakes and learn good skills to take your fermentation to the next level! All levels of experience are welcome, as you are guided through the whole fermentation process from start to finish. Take home your own jars of delicious ferments, alongside the confidence and skills to create delicious fermented sauerkraut at home.
Event.long_description:
Esther has perfected the art of fermentation, running a successful wholesale business supplying many of Wellington's best cafes and restaurants with top quality sauerkraut and fermented condiments. In this fun, engaging and hands-on class, learn how to flavor and enhance sauerkraut recipes for a winning batch every time, troubleshoot common mistakes and learn some good skills to take your fermentation to the next level! 
 
All skill levels and experience are welcome, as you are taken through the whole fermentation process from start to finish. Take home your own jars of delicious ferments, along the confidence and skills to create delicious fermented sauerkraut at home, plus ideas and recipes to make the most of enjoying your creations.

Event.wellington_story: The love for travel is ingrained in Kiwis with over 75% of New Zealanders holding a passport pre-Covid, and one million Kiwis living abroad. Wellington's love for international cuisine and culture is clearly present in the plethora of cafes and restaurants that make up our lively dining scene. With the pandemic setting in around the world, throwing travel plans into a state of flux, many Kiwis are still yearning for the ease of travel pre-Covid days and waiting eagerly for borders to reopen. Mockingbird pays homage to the travel Wellingtonians have done, to bring back fond memories of long haul flights and of course, the plane food which - love it or hate it - is an eponymous part of the journey itself.

Event.wellington_story: Neo Café & Eatery are here to celebrate the flat white and the good work of the Wellington coffee pioneers of the early 1990s. It was their efforts and love for coffee that led to the innovation of this beloved morning staple  - now a coffee lovers’ addiction worldwide. For cafés and baristas, the flat white has become the measuring stick for excellence. The evolution of brewing equipment and coffee quality has only added fuel to the fire of perfection. This year, in a playful take on the quintessential coffee-and-cake combo, Neo offers a melded dish designed to take you on a journey of delight and surprise; one that is reminiscent of those cuddly feelings you get when your lips meet the silky-smooth foam of the flat white, followed by the intense espresso hit of blended coffee, chocolate and malt flavours, forming a perfect balance as you head towards the bottom of the cup - or in this case, plate.

Event.title: The Wines They Are A Changing
Event.keywords:
Wine
Tasting Menu
Noble Rot
Event.one_sentence_description: Compare & contrast wines of different ages and discover what happens to wine over time.
Event.short_description: Wine is in a constant state of flux. Bottled young and often opened soon thereafter, but what happens when wine is left to develop and change with time? The Noble Wine-olojists have selected pairs of the same wine, one newly bottled current release and one bottled for many years to demonstrate the differences in development stages. Taste ten wines perfectly complemented by head chef Shanti Saraf’s delicious five-course tasting fare that will enhance wines both young and old. Wine, like people, changes with age and some get better!
Event.long_description: Wine is in a constant state of flux. Bottled young and often opened soon thereafter, but what happens when wine is left to develop and change with time? The Noble Wine-olojists have selected pairs of the same wine, one newly bottled current release and one bottled for many years to demonstrate the differences in development stages. Taste ten wines perfectly complemented by head chef Shanti Saraf’s delicious five-course tasting fare that will enhance wines both young and old. Wine, like people, changes with age and some get better!
Event.event_title: The Wines They Are A Changing

Event.title: Changing The Language Of Wine
Event.keywords:
Wine-oji®
Wine
Noble Rot
Event.one_sentence_description: Changing the language of wine with Wine-oji.
Event.short_description: The language of wine; romantic, mysterious, enticing, yet often confusing! What if you could know exactly what the wine will taste like when you buy it? Wine-oji is on a mission to solve this problem one wine at a time. Join the team at Noble Rot as they take a wine and compare its “classic review” with their very own Wine-oji profile to show you just how helpful this new, visual language for wine is. Wines will be accompanied by cheese, charcuterie and Noble Rot's famous chicken liver parfait. Plus, you get to take home your very own Wine-oji® Library.
Event.long_description: The language of wine; romantic, mysterious, enticing, yet often confusing! What’s the difference between 93 points with a gold sticker and 92 points with a silver? They taste pretty much the same right? What if you could know exactly what the wine will taste like when you buy it? Wine-oji is on a mission to solve this problem one wine at a time. Join the team at Noble Rot as they take a wine and compare its “classic review” with their very own Wine-oji profile to show you just how helpful this new, visual language for wine is. Wines will be accompanied by cheese, charcuterie and Noble Rot's famous chicken liver parfait. Plus, you get to take home your very own Wine-oji® Library. Welcome to the future of wine.

Event.title: The Greatness Of Grenache
Event.keywords:
Wine
Grenache
Noble Rot
Event.one_sentence_description: Explore the wonderful world of Grenache right here in Wellington.
Event.short_description: All hail Grenache. Living in the shadows of more famous varieties like Pinot Noir and Cabernet Sauvignon, Grenache is the quiet achiever of wine. For Noble Rot’s Josh Pointon, Grenache is ready for a change in status! Whether you’re in Spain drinking Garnacha Tinta or Garnatxa, in Italy drinking Cannonau, or in Australia drinking it as a blend in a GSM with Syrah and Mourvedre, Grenache has the qualities to be outstanding. Taste your way around the world of Grenache while enjoying a five-course tasting menu designed with the great grape in mind.
Event.long_description: All hail Grenache! Living in the shadows of more famous varieties like Pinot Noir and Cabernet Sauvignon, Grenache represents the quiet achiever rather than the rock star. For Noble Rot’s Josh Pointon, Grenache is ready for a change in status. Whether you’re in Spain drinking Garnacha Tinta or Garnatxa, in Italy drinking Cannonau, or Australia drinking it as a blend in a GSM with Syrah and Mourvedre, Grenache has the qualities to be outstanding. Taste your way around the world of Grenache while enjoying a five-course tasting menu designed with the great grape in mind and get ready to bend the knee.

Event.short_description: The Winemakers Long Lunch is back and Noble Rot is changing it up for 2022. The team have invited the pick of the vintage from New Zealand’s wine engine room, Marlborough. Prepare yourself for a big afternoon of fine food, tall tales and wines that speak of people and place. The Marlborough bunch are raiding the winery cellars to bring an array of special bottles to share with you. Event.title: Get Him To The Greek!
Event.keywords:
Greek
Wine
Noble Rot
Event.one_sentence_description: Join us at Noble Rot for a Greek wine experience not to be missed!
Event.short_description: Russell Brand got there and so will you! Noble Rot is shaking at the Peloponnese with excitement about this event and proud to be teaming up with Kieran Clarkin, owner of Cellar Days and importer of fine Greek wines. From the mountainous north of mainland Greece to the many islands, the country has a vast amount of exciting wine to try. Kieran will be showcasing varieties that you have probably never heard of, let alone be able to pronounce. Event.wellington_story: Wellington in the 1950s was heavily radio-influenced as television was still in its infancy until the 1960s. American music was incredibly popular at the time due to a marked shift away from all things British. The Wellington Town Hall hosted regular dances in which "young men performed backspins and dolphins" to the cheering girls hoping to “fill their dance cards”, so they could in turn "pump their knees and flap their arms like chicken wings" to the popular tunes. Musicians like Dean Martin and Frank Sinatra - some of the greatest Italian American artists - carved out a new dance culture for Wellington's youth. Nolita's Festival Dish is a take on Italian food with a New York element, taking a classic dish from the 1950s and giving it a modern twist and shake - a plant based Wellingtonesque twist to the Italian classic osso bucco.

Event.wellington_story: The Purple Onion operated for a decade between 1964 and 1974 as a late-night dance and striptease bar located across the road from where Ombra is today on Cuba Street. It was the venue that Wellington's beloved Carmen Rupe first made her mark and the area was generally at the forefront of Wellington's drag scene. Representing this evolution of the wider upper Cuba and Vivian Street area from a red-light district to be avoided, to one of the city's liveliest restaurant spots, The Purple Onion has inspired this year's dish - a pasta dish with onion at its core.

Event.wellington_story: Pravda was the name of a Soviet-era newspaper that translates to 'The Truth'. In current times, it is a cafe, bar and bistro offering the honest simplicity of bistro food, wines from around the world and the welcome of an old friend. To the team at Pravda, nothing is more welcoming and honest than a simple Slavic Shashlik -  a timeless favourite of skewered and grilled meat.

Event.short_description: Every Wellingtonian knows where the best cheese scones can be found. Many will point to Pravda Cafe. Event.one_sentence_description: A few mates coming together to encourage conversation around mental health over dinner.
Event.short_description: Mental health is still in many ways a taboo subject, especially in the hospitality industry. Together with "help from our friends", Egmont St Eatery are creating a space for dialogue around mental health. Enjoy five courses with beverage matches, presented by an all-star cast of Wellington's best chefs and front of house. Come together over delicious food and drink in the historic Public Trust Hall and be entertained by speakers, musicians and performers at a gala dinner to remember. All profits from the event are being donated to Feelings for Life to normalise open dialogue around mental health in the community.
Event.long_description:

Event.wellington_story: Out of the dust of the 1980s stock market crash, and into the early 1990s a classic Kiwi slogan "Absolutely Positively Wellington" was born, designed to highlight Wellingtonians who were succeeding in business despite the grim environment. Fast forward to the past two years of the COVID pandemic, and the economic environment is challenged, and some people find themselves on opposite divides due to differences in ideas and beliefs. It's time to remember the "Absolutely Positively Wellington" slogan and how we can come together to overcome challenges, just like the good old Wellingtonians did more than 30 years ago. "Absolutely Positively Wellington" has inspired the team at Rock Yard to create their Festival Dish, with crispy crackling to represent the difficult situations we are all facing. But underneath this hard surface is the super tender meat, representing the heart and soul of Wellingtonians.

Event.kid_friendly: Yes but they must be accompanied by an adult
Event.one_sentence_description: The grand Tour: A Culinary trip through the Med
Event.short_description:
The Good Ship Salty sets sail for the great ports of the Mediterranean. This five-course dinner begins with a welcome drink in Crete, the biggest of the Greek islands, then island-hop to the Italian oasis that is Sicily. Following the coast to the Gorgeous Port City of Marseille. The main courses are served in the Cultural wonder that is San Sebastien, returning to home Port, the exotic Casablanca in Morocco.
Join the crew for an evening of fine food, live music, frivolity, and adventure, taking in the virtual sights and sounds of the Mediterranean. All aboard.

Scopa is a Pizzeria staying true to their Italian roots, but not being defined by them. Their story is about being both Italian and Wellingtonian in the same breath; about being prepared to evolve with the times but to always keep a bit of yourself, your ‘base’ if you will.
This time around, the team have decided to REALLY bend the rules on what a pizza can be. With a nod to the Wellington kebab shops and to flex their own culinary chains so far, even the Italian gods won't believe what they've done! Who doesn't love pizza? Who doesn't love a Kebab? ‘Ma' Donner, I can't believe they are doing this!’.

Event.wellington_story: 1865 was a seminal year in Wellington's history becoming the capital of New Zealand and opening its port to supply the world. The same year coincided with the end of the American Civil War. A time when families, friends and loved ones joined together to celebrate both here and in America. It was the time when the American apple pie was centre stage in those culinary celebrations. Southern Cross are bringing together a two-course group dining experience to mark the rise of the celebratory dessert - the first course is a shared American feast then followed by their twist on the all American apple pie.

Event.wellington_story:
Esther James was an exceptional individual known for the diversity of her achievements. In the 1930s she became a national celebrity during her sponsored walk of the length of New Zealand to promote local products. On her journey, she had to take a week’s rest in Wellington due to an injury. “Such was the generosity of her overnight hosts - usually prominent farmers or business people - that she claimed to have gained a stone (7kg) in weight during the 2000 km walk. Consuming only New Zealand produce, she most missed cups of tea”. 

Tea rooms and milk bars were popular in Wellington streets between 1900-1950 and Esther James could have visited any during her stay in Wellington. t Lounge by Dilmah imagines what would have been on offer if they were around to serve Esther.

Event.keywords: withwild.co.nz - live in the next 4 weeks
Event.kid_friendly: Yes but they must be accompanied by an adult
Event.one_sentence_description: From the Wild, for the Wild. With Wild
Event.short_description:
Every year ‘introduced’ wild animals are culled to help protect precious native flora and fauna and create ecosystems that enable our native birds to thrive in our national parks. With Wild is honouring and respecting these free-roaming animals by acknowledging them as a valuable food resource.
Hosted by With Wild co-founders alongside chefs Tom Hishon (Kingi, Orphans Kitchen, Daily Bread) and Dariush Lolaiy (Cazador), enjoy the unique flavours and tastes that is Fiordland Wapiti. Each course is matched with artisan Aotearoa craft beer, cider, or wine.
A percentage of every ticket will be donated to the Fiordland Wapiti Foundation.

Event.wellington_story: Wellington's cafe culture is legendary, springing up in the 1950s with immigrants arriving bringing exotic new foods and espresso machines. They began initially as milk bars, over time becoming more like the cafés we recognise today, and were hubs for artists, writers and musicians, who would while the hours away late into the night debating the arts and hot topics. Such artists have inspired the chefs at The Botanist, who are bringing their artistry to food with each course being represented by a different artist. Based on art by Jackson Pollock, whose style was abstract impressionism, and applied to both the appearance of the dish and through strange and interesting flavour profiles this is The Botanist’s way of acknowledging the birth of the Wellington cafe scene, through the marriage of art and food.

Event.title: An Evening with Jeroboam
Event.keywords: beer, craft beer, the hudson, choice bros, collab
Event.one_sentence_description: New beers will be brewed, perfect food pairings will be matched and all in an intimate setting at The Hudson.
Event.short_description: An evening with Jeroboam is the byproduct of a perfect pairing between two Wellington Hopso spots. Choice Bros brewers will be creating three specialty beers for this event, presented in Jeroboam bottles alongside a three-course meal put together by the team at The Hudson.
Event.long_description:
Choice Bros & The Hudson have been teammates throughout the years,  ever-growing & changing & experimenting with new ideas. Introducing new concepts and exciting new flavours to the ever thirsty & hungry Wellingtonians.
An evening with Jeroboam is the byproduct of a perfect pairing between two Wellington Hopso spots. The Choice Bros brewers will be brewing three specialty beers for this event which are served in Jereboam bottles alongside the perfect food pairings for an intimate evening at The Hudson.

Beers featured:
Israeli Couscous Table Beer - 3.5%
This will be light, refreshing and fun, a low ABV aperitif.
25% of the grain will be substituted for Israeli couscous (hilarious, I know).
We'll add pomegranate molasses at the end of the boil.
It will be aged on mint, pistachios, salt, and cucumber.

Qamar Al-Din sour - 5.5%
A sweet apricot and rose water sour. This is based on a traditional drink, usually consumed after Ramadan.
We will use the base recipe from our Superfast Jellyfish series of sours, and substitute the usual fruit with an apricot puree that we will make, and a splash of rose water.

Date Barleywine - 10%
The big, thick, sweet boy at the end of the evening. We will make oleo saccharum (a sugar and orange peel syrup) to add at the end of the boil.
We will vac-pack vanilla, oak chips, dates and bourbon, let them marry for a month, and age the beer on this mixture.

Food featured:

Cous Cous Table Beer
Sharing Mezze – Selection of well-known Middle Eastern delights.

Qamar Al-Din Sour
Persian Lamb with Saffron and Barberry Rice

Date Barleywine
Kataifi with Honey syrup & Sesame crumb

Event.wellington_story: By the end of the 1960s, there were dozens of coffee shops, bars and lounges in central Wellington. But with the advent of television in the early 1960s coffee houses were on the decline. At the same time, liquor laws were relaxed following a licensing referendum in 1967, with hotels able to remain open until 10 pm and serve food. Restaurants became more sophisticated and appealing to the new, more affluent and well-travelled generation of the 1970s. The Library has taken inspiration from these heady days with their Festival Dish banoffee pie, meets a new-fangled culinary technique (in the 1970s that is), fondue. Designed for sharing between two.

Event.one_sentence_description: Let us whisk you off to Paris in the 1930s. A celebration of all of the libraries favourite things cocktails, books, puddings and jazz.

Event.wellington_story: The Gear Meat Factory in Petone commonly known as the ''stink factory'' was founded in 1874 by James Gear. Modern-day Petone was born in 1981 when the abattoir closed, and workers moved North to find other jobs in freezing works and other industries. Petone’s gentrification got underway as upwardly mobile young families moved in, and it is now known for its diverse restaurants and café scene. The Victoria Tavern’s dish reflects the changes in Petone through the modern changes in foods, showcasing the delicious meals that come out of the southern end of Hutt Valley.

Event.wellington_story: ‘Nana Ray’ was a humble and soulful home chef that immigrated to Wellington in 1951, bringing with her a Ukrainian Jewish heritage. She kept her culture alive through cooking for new friends and family, and by sharing her recipes in a cookbook collection by Gisi Hirschfeld, published in Wellington in 1999, alongside other Jewish immigrants. Nana Ray was a huge influence on her grandson, Thomas Monk, head chef at The White Swan Country Hotel and he shares her passion for soulful food made from the heart. Tom’s Festival dish reinvents Ray’s traditional chicken soup recipe using modern cooking techniques and the use of fresh local ingredients – a melting pot of old-world meets new-world, with layers of vibrancy and of unique pops of flavour.

Event.wellington_story: The Thistle Inn has stood on Town Acre 515 since 1840 when William Couper served his first rounds. Then it was just a single-storey, gabled building with attics above. Until the 1876 reclamation, it faced the beach and people walked, rowed or paddled here to slake their thirst and their appetite. William was a keen hunter and was often found in the hills around Wellington hunting wild boar and deer which he dutifully butchered for his wife to serve up at the pub much to the delight of punters. Mrs Couper would often use the wild pork for her Sunday roast, not quite a porchetta but much loved all the same. The shape of New Zealand was used as a marketing tool to attract Italian migrants with a 19th-century promoter of Italian immigration showing how New Zealand bears a resemblance to Italy, by turning it upside down with "the foot end facing up", Wellington was a popular choice to live for a lot of Italians hence the name of our dish. This porchetta dish is a nod to William and his wife and the Italians who immigrated to Wellington during this time to help make Wellington what it is today.

Event.long_description:
Calling all chefs aged 9-15 years.VIVISTOP is on the hunt for the best burger in town - can you create it? What makes a perfect burger? Is it sweet or savoury? Egg or no egg? VIVISTOP are looking for young chefs to help them design the best burger Wellington has ever tasted over this two-day workshop. On the first day discover the incredible world of burgers and learn all about the delicious ingredients. On the second day create your very own burger from scratch!

This is a two-day weekend workshop - participants are expected to take part on both days to complete the workshop. 
First workshop 13th - 14th of August; 10 am - 12 pm
Second workshop 20th - 21st of August; 10am - 12pm

Booking either the 13th or 20th of August will grant you a spot for the following day.

Event.title: Chocolatier & Wine
Event.keywords:
chocolate
craft chocolate
local chocolate
New Zealand chocolate
Chocolate and wine tasting
Event.one_sentence_description: Chocolatier and Wine
Event.short_description:
You've heard of "Paint and Wine", this is "Chocolatier and Wine"! You'll be challenged to temper your own chocolate, mould your own bars, choose your bar toppings, before sealing the deal by hand wrapping your bars to take home with you.
While your chocolate bars are cooling down, you will learn about the parallels between cocoa beans and chocolate and grapes and wine, how flavour is in a state of flux depending on cocoa bean variety, origin, and harvest.
Tickets include two glasses of wine, three custom chocolate bars and a chocolate and wine matching/tasting session.
Event.long_description:
You've heard of "Paint and Wine", this is "Chocolatier and Wine"!
Let Wellington Chocolate Factory chocolatiers help you craft and wrap your own three chocolate bars, while enjoying a glass of Palliser Estate wine. You'll be challenged to temper your own chocolate, mould your own bars, and be your artistic self, choosing and arranging your bar toppings from an array of ingredients, before sealing the deal by hand wrapping your three bars to take home with you. Chocolatier status achieved!
While your chocolate bars are cooling down, you will learn about the parallels between cocoa beans and chocolate and grapes and wine, how flavour is in a state of flux depending on cocoa bean variety, origin, and harvest. During this intermission there will also be a chocolate and wine matching/tasting session. 
Tickets include two glasses of wine and three custom chocolate bars.

Event.short_description: Cazador and Garage Project bring you a luxurious four-course banquet of wild food, natural wine, and wild-ferment beer. Retreat from the quotidian, and give yourself over to the altar of decadence. Sit amongst the foeders (giant oak barrels) of the Garage Project Wild Workshop and devote yourself to the feast before you; a long lazy lunch from one of Auckland's oldest restaurants, Cazador, paired with natural wines, wild ferment beers, and a sherry on top. Forget the outside world - it's time to feast.

Event.title: Ngā Kai o Te Wao ō Tāne o Hirānia
Event.keywords: Māori cuisine, indigenous ingredients, native, Zealandia, Joe McLeod
Event.one_sentence_description: An indigenous cultural culinary adventure set in the picturesque surroundings of Zealandia Te Māra a Tāne.
Event.short_description: An indigenous cultural culinary adventure set in the picturesque surroundings of Zealandia Te Māra a Tāne. Wellington chef, Joe McLeod (Ngāi Tūhoe), is a tohunga (expert) in indigenous ingredients and contemporary Māori cuisine and shares his passion for enhancing and preserving the indigenous culinary culture of Aotearoa New Zealand in this unique nine-course dining experience. Indigenous ingredients are sourced locally and sustainably from across Wellington, New Zealand and the Chatham Islands, and cooked according to Māori culinary practices and techniques. Chef McLeod will discuss the connection of each dish to Zealandia, Māori cuisine and Wellington arts. A selection of local wines and non-alcoholic beverages will compliment the menu.
Event.long_description:
An indigenous cultural culinary adventure set in the picturesque surroundings of Zealandia Te Māra a Tāne. Wellington chef, Joe McLeod (Ngāi Tūhoe), is a tohunga (expert) in indigenous ingredients and contemporary Māori cuisine, and shares his passion for enhancing and preserving the indigenous culinary culture of Aotearoa New Zealand in this unique nine-course dining experience. 
 
Indigenous ingredients are sourced locally and sustainably from across Wellington, New Zealand and the Chatham Islands, and cooked according to Māori culinary practices and techniques. Ingredients are inspired by the Zealandia sanctuary to sea journey, taking care to protect their unique status and symbolic importance to the Wellington region.  
 
The menu has been designed around the nine motifs chosen identifying their place in our capital, matched with our unique culinary Māori connection to Zealandia and how we will show case tonight's dinner to honour our artists.
 
Chef McLeod will present to guests and discuss the connection of each dish to Zealandia, Māori cuisine and Wellington arts. 
 
Each dish is paired with a selection of local wines and non-alcoholic beverages to compliment the menu.
Event.event_title: Ngā Kai o Te Wao ō Tāne o Hirānia
